WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.560
[Amit Varma]: When I was growing up, I thought history was something that happened in the past.

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:13.880
[Amit Varma]: At its worst, it's a bunch of dates and boring factoids.

00:00:13.880 --> 00:00:18.200
[Amit Varma]: At its best, it's wild, exciting stories of mad kings and dissolute courtesans and

00:00:18.200 --> 00:00:19.200
[Amit Varma]: entertaining battles.

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:23.120
[Amit Varma]: When we look at history, I thought we are looking back.

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:28.200
[Amit Varma]: But anyone listening to this podcast in 2020 knows that this is not true.

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:32.560
[Amit Varma]: History gave us the DNA of every single conflict in the modern world.

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:35.520
[Amit Varma]: History has been weaponized in our politics.

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:40.720
[Amit Varma]: And indeed, history keeps changing, depending on what narrative one wants to believe, to

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:46.040
[Amit Varma]: the extent that I sometimes wonder if all history is just mythology, and whether what

00:00:46.040 --> 00:00:51.600
[Amit Varma]: happened in the past is both utterly unimportant and also utterly crucial.

00:00:51.600 --> 00:00:56.920
[Amit Varma]: In India, nowhere do we find these contestations as in the case of Mughal history.

00:00:56.920 --> 00:01:01.520
[Amit Varma]: Regardless of where the Mughal dynasty itself originated, should we regard them as Indian

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:07.440
[Amit Varma]: rulers from whom we took so much that is beautiful about our culture, from our language, our

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:11.680
[Amit Varma]: cuisines, and even our clothes, such as the elegant churidar kurtas worn by our Prime

00:01:11.680 --> 00:01:12.760
[Amit Varma]: Minister?

00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:18.240
[Amit Varma]: Or should we look at the Mughals as invaders who destroyed temples and massacred Hindus,

00:01:18.240 --> 00:01:23.520
[Amit Varma]: and who must be avenged by the othering of modern Indian Muslims?

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:29.320
[Amit Varma]: This is a political question, but it can only be answered through history.

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:37.280
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:38.280
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:38.280 --> 00:01:41.280
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:41.280 --> 00:01:45.160
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:50.720
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is a journalist and author, Manimukta Sharma, whose recent book, Allahu

00:01:50.720 --> 00:01:57.080
[Amit Varma]: Akbar, considers the legacy of Akbar in the light of the recent revisionism around him.

00:01:57.080 --> 00:02:03.120
[Amit Varma]: As Manimukta writes in his introduction, Jawaharlal Nehru once described Akbar as, quote, the

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:08.520
[Amit Varma]: great representative of the old Indian ideal of a synthesis of differing elements and their

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:11.680
[Amit Varma]: fusion into a common nationality, stop quote.

00:02:11.680 --> 00:02:17.080
[Amit Varma]: Indeed, this has been the traditional view of Akbar the Great, as he is called, referring

00:02:17.080 --> 00:02:23.240
[Amit Varma]: to his syncretism and tolerance, and yet he has also been recently described as, quote,

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:27.520
[Amit Varma]: a genocidal monster no better than Hitler, stop quote.

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:30.080
[Amit Varma]: Which of these is closer to the truth?

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:32.680
[Amit Varma]: Are they both true to differing degrees?

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:33.680
[Amit Varma]: And does it matter?

00:02:33.680 --> 00:02:40.760
[Amit Varma]: I shall ask Manimukta these questions and more after a quick commercial break.

